# ============================================================
# DATAGLOW — static-host response headers
# ============================================================
# Netlify / Cloudflare Pages "_headers" format. Hosts that read this file will
# apply these real HTTP response headers; sw.js injects the same cross-origin
# isolation headers as a host-agnostic fallback for hosts that ignore it.
#
# WHY these headers: DuckDB-WASM's threaded / exception-handling build wants
# `SharedArrayBuffer`, which the browser only exposes when the page is
# cross-origin isolated. Isolation requires BOTH a Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy
# and a Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy header on the top-level document. They MUST
# be sent as HTTP headers — <meta http-equiv> does not work for COOP/COEP.
#
# WHY COEP=credentialless (not require-corp): the app self-hosts everything it
# needs on a normal page load (fonts included, self-hosted under assets/fonts/),
# but the opt-in Python/R/Story tabs pull Pyodide, WebR and WebLLM from public
# CDNs. Under `require-corp` every such cross-origin response would need its own CORP/CORS
# header or it is blocked; `credentialless` keeps isolation on while letting
# those no-credentials cross-origin fetches through, so the opt-in runtimes keep
# working without routing any user data off the machine.
/*
  Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy: same-origin
  Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy: credentialless

# Serve the DuckDB-WASM binaries as application/wasm so the browser can use
# streaming compilation (WebAssembly.instantiateStreaming). A wrong content type
# here is one way a host ends up rejecting or mis-serving the .wasm asset.
/assets/duckdb/*.wasm
  Content-Type: application/wasm
